Abstract:
The multivariable autoregressive ﬁlter problem asks for a polynomial p(z) = p(z1, . . . , zd)
without roots in the closed d-disk based on prescribed Fourier coeﬃcients of its spectral density
function 1/|p(z)|2. The conditions derived in this paper for the construction of a degree one
symmetric polynomial reveal a major divide between the case of at most two variables vs. the
the case of three or more variables. The latter involves multivariable elliptic functions, while
the former (due to [J. S. Geronimo and H. J. Woerdeman, Ann. of Math. (2), 160(3):839–
906, 2004]) only involve polynomials. The three variable case is treated with more detail, and
